  },
  {
    "question": "What is the aggregate method in amortized analysis and how is the amortized cost per operation determined?",
    "answer": "The aggregate method in amortized analysis involves first analyzing the total cost of an entire sequence of operations, then calculating the amortized cost per operation by dividing this total cost by the number of operations. This approach provides an average cost per operation in the worst case, even when different types of operations are present in the sequence."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the accounting method work for analyzing the cost of operations in a data structure?",
    "answer": "The accounting method assigns an amortized cost to each individual operation before executing the sequence, ensuring that the sum of all amortized costs is at least the sum of actual costs for all operations. Extra cost (credit) from an operation where the amortized cost exceeds the actual cost is stored with the object in the data structure and used to pay for future operations where actual cost may exceed the amortized cost. This ensures an upper bound on the total true cost of the sequence."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the accounting method explain the cost of insertions in a dynamic array that periodically resizes?",
    "answer": "In a dynamic array, the accounting method assigns an amortized cost to each insertion; for example, if the actual cost of an insertion is 1 unless resizing is required, the method overcharges each operation (for example, charging 3 for each insertion). The surplus from insertions that do not trigger resizing is saved to pay for expensive resizing (copying all elements to a new array of double the size). This prepayment ensures the average (amortized) cost of each insertion remains constant, even though some insertions require expensive resizing. The key point is that frequent, cheap insertions accumulate savings to cover infrequent but costly resizing operations, keeping the average cost per operation low. This method applies widely in data structures that have operations with occasional high cost amidst frequent low-cost operations."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the accounting method work when analyzing binary counter increment operations?",
    "answer": "For a binary counter, every time you increment the counter, you may need to flip several bits from 1 to 0 until you reach a 0 bit to flip to 1. Using the accounting method, you can assign a higher amortized cost (for example, 2) to every increment operation. When a bit is flipped from 0 to 1, you pay for the current flip and prepay (save an extra unit) for the flip back from 1 to 0. Through this scheme, the real cost of each operation is effectively distributed across all increments, ensuring that even in the worst cases when multiple bits flip, the total cost over n operations is O(n), making the amortized cost per increment constant. This technique is useful in the analysis of counters and bit-manipulation algorithms."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the potential method handle credits and costs in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "In the potential method, we maintain credit as potential energy associated with the structure as a whole. The cost of each operation is calculated by considering both the actual cost and the change in the potential function. As described, the cost of each will then be T(n)n, where T(n) is a function that accounts for the state of the data structure and n is the number of operations."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is the accounting method in amortized analysis and how are the operations charged?",
    "answer": "The accounting method in amortized analysis involves charging the operations directly. Instead of associating potential energy with the structure, we charge each operation a specific amount (possibly more than its actual cost) and track the excess as a credit that can be used to pay for more expensive future operations. This ensures the total amount charged covers all actual costs."
  }
]
